    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3183906511" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3183906511" />
    <a title="Tony" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/97932047-tony"><img alt="Tony" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1563897940p2/97932047.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3183906511?book_show_action=true">Feb 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tony" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tony" href="/user/show/97932047-tony">Tony</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/97932047-tony?shelf=2020-read-shelf">2020-read-shelf</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3183906511" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6962199674916626479">After reading Long Road to Mercy by David Baldacci, all I can really say is...it was just OK. It seemed like a story that didn&apos;t know WHAT kind of story it wanted to be...at first I was intrigued by the serial killer teaser, then it switched to a missing person/murder mystery (which I was really excited for), then it turned into a global-intrigue thriller and ended up a really sad Dan Brown wannabe conspiracy. It felt like WAY TOO MUCH crammed into a thin story. <br/><br/>Without rehashing the entire stor</span>
  <span id="freeText6962199674916626479" style="display:none">After reading Long Road to Mercy by David Baldacci, all I can really say is...it was just OK. It seemed like a story that didn't know WHAT kind of story it wanted to be...at first I was intrigued by the serial killer teaser, then it switched to a missing person/murder mystery (which I was really excited for), then it turned into a global-intrigue thriller and ended up a really sad Dan Brown wannabe conspiracy. It felt like WAY TOO MUCH crammed into a thin story. <br /><br />Without rehashing the entire story, I'll just pick out a few hits/misses. There WILL be some spoilers (sorry, I usually try to avoid them). I DID like the main character, Atlee Pine. I thought her back story was great and added some depth to her character. I had a great picture of her in my mind and thought she seemed real. Sung Nam Chung was also an interesting (but minor) character, though I kept picturing a mini version of the Bond villain "Odd Job". However, while I enjoyed the interaction and fight sequences between them, it just didn't make sense how they could be after the same thing and yet have this "conflict". Why not work together to locate and stop the "Nuke" plot.<br />The REST of the character ensemble seemed like cardboard cut-outs from any thriller novel. Most were quite bland and almost cheesy at times. <br /><br />The action of the story kept moving and I did find myself "sucked in" which makes for a good thriller. The PLOT started out fantastic and then took an "eye-rolling" stumble in Maryland when the characters discover the "conspiracy" and locate a "Do-gooder" association called SFG: Society For Good. Yes, that's right, Society For Good....Really?! That's the best name for a secret organization of wealthy benefactors combating injustice in the world? It sounds like something a 6th grader would come up with for a comic book they doodled for a class project. Here, the story falls off the rails and sinks into a SpikeTV/NetFlix low budget thriller. Disappointing.<br /><br />I so enjoyed the MYSTERY story that started the book and the majestic description of the Grand Canyon. I could picture the landscape and feel the hot desert air, and THAT is what draws me into a good story, especially since I have NEVER been out West. But once we reached the crazy conspiracy, I felt like Baldacci wasn't even trying anymore. It just seemed too formulaic and ....well, average. Even the big climatic confrontation in the end seemed dull and unrealistic. I mean, the government is going to these lengths to cover up a conspiracy to launch us into a war with North Korea and a DVD of the villains confessing is going to STOP everything. "Don't do this or I'm gonna tell on you!" Oh please! And not only does she stop the threat, but gets all these concessions as well, like the Bruce Willis' crew in Armageddon ("...and we don't want to pay taxes...ever"). <br /><br />The story started out really strong, but in the end was just another so-so thrill ride. I AM hoping to read more of the character Atlee Pine. I just hope the next story is as exciting as the first HALF of this story, but continues that excitement through the entire book. Just 3 stars from me.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6962199674916626479" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


